So I've come up with what I think is the easiest way to understand Hyperbolic space.

00:24.000 --> 00:31.000
Let's start off with Euclidean in spherical spaces in two dimensions, and then Hyperbolic space in three dimensions come naturally later.

00:31.000 --> 00:38.000
So here's just a regular flatland 2D Euclidean plane that goes on in every direction and has no curvature.

00:38.000 --> 00:43.000
But if we add some positive curvature, we get a spherical shell.

00:43.000 --> 00:49.000
This is not a solid ball, there's no inside or outside, just an infinitely thin two-dimensional shell.

00:49.000 --> 00:55.000
We're only looking at it in 3D because we are higher-dimensional beings looking down at the flatlanders.

00:55.000 --> 01:03.000
You might think this is really similar to us living on the surface of Earth, but there's actually a big difference, and it has to do with light and lines.

01:03.000 --> 01:07.000
Think about light bending around the curved space of a black hole.

01:07.000 --> 01:13.000
Light always travels in the shortest path in a straight line, it's just that the space itself is curved.

01:13.000 --> 01:22.000
So if the Earth actually had a spherical spacetime, then looking out at the horizon, the light you see would actually travel all the way around the Earth.

01:22.000 --> 01:26.000
In fact, there wouldn't be a horizon anymore. Things would be a lot weirder.

01:26.000 --> 01:29.000
Another way to think about curvature is with tiling.

01:29.000 --> 01:33.000
There's only three ways to tile the Euclidean plane with regular polygons.

01:33.000 --> 01:39.000
Four squares at a vertex, six triangles at a vertex, or three hexagons at a vertex.

01:39.000 --> 01:47.000
If you were to say, try pentagons, you'd find that there's not enough space for four and too much gap for three.

01:47.000 --> 01:53.000
But those gaps could get filled with spherical curvature, and you have the familiar dodecahedron.

01:56.000 --> 01:59.000
We can also do three squares around each vertex.

02:03.000 --> 02:05.000
Three triangles.

02:09.000 --> 02:11.000
Four triangles.

02:14.000 --> 02:16.000
Or five triangles.

02:19.000 --> 02:23.000
And just a reminder, all these edges are straight lines.

02:23.000 --> 02:27.000
Everything lives on that two-dimensional shell, and there's no third dimension to curve into.

02:27.000 --> 02:30.000
We're only using it to help visualize the space.

02:30.000 --> 02:33.000
So now let's move on to hyperbolic space.

02:33.000 --> 02:38.000
The theme you'll see for the rest of the video is that for everything weird about spherical geometry,

02:38.000 --> 02:41.000
the opposite is true for hyperbolic geometry.

02:41.000 --> 02:47.000
For example, you just saw that we could have fewer squares around each vertex compared to Euclidean space.

02:47.000 --> 02:50.000
So in hyperbolic space, we can have more.

02:50.000 --> 02:53.000
But how could you cram in another square?

02:53.000 --> 02:58.000
Well, maybe we can do the same trick as the sphere and just bring it out into the third dimension.

02:58.000 --> 03:01.000
We can, and here's how it looks.

03:01.000 --> 03:05.000
This is hyperbolic crochet, courtesy of Mrs. Parade.

03:05.000 --> 03:08.000
You can see how five squares meet at every vertex now.

03:08.000 --> 03:12.000
But it's still hard to visualize everything even with a 3D model,

03:12.000 --> 03:17.000
because if you try to flatten it in one area, everywhere else starts curving.

03:17.000 --> 03:24.000
It's impossible to see it all at once, and it gets even worse as we look at bigger and bigger pieces of the hyperbolic plane.

03:24.000 --> 03:29.000
Though it does give you a sense of how much larger hyperbolic space is compared to Euclidean.

03:29.000 --> 03:36.000
And don't forget, these are all still two-dimensional geometries that we're using in extra dimension to help visualize.

03:36.000 --> 03:43.000
If we want to go up to 3D spaces, then good luck trying to visualize the 3D surface of a 4D hypersphere,

03:43.000 --> 03:46.000
or whatever this mess would look like in four dimensions.

03:46.000 --> 03:52.000
In order to make any sense of things at this point, we're going to need a different way to visualize the hyperbolic plane.

03:52.000 --> 03:55.000
The trick we're going to use is projection.

03:55.000 --> 04:01.000
You're probably familiar with 3D projection, that is taking a 3D object and projecting it to your eyeball or a screen.

04:01.000 --> 04:09.000
After all, you're looking at this cube on your 2D screen, but you still perceive it as 3D, even though we've completely distorted it.

04:09.000 --> 04:13.000
I mean, this is supposed to be a square, but look at all these angles.

04:13.000 --> 04:15.000
Is the cube warped? Of course not.

04:15.000 --> 04:21.000
It's just that projected angles and distances can change depending on where you look at it from, and what projection you use.

04:21.000 --> 04:26.000
Similarly, we can project a curved geometry to a flat one, or vice versa.

04:26.000 --> 04:33.000
You're probably familiar with the Mercader projection for a sphere, but as you can tell, it introduces distortions.

04:33.000 --> 04:39.000
Greenland and Africa look about the same size here, but Africa is actually 14 times larger.

04:39.000 --> 04:45.000
Unfortunately, it's impossible to map a sphere to a plane without introducing distortion,

04:45.000 --> 04:53.000
and that's why there's hundreds of different projections, because either distances, angles, areas, or shapes will get distorted,

04:53.000 --> 04:56.000
and which compromise you want depends on the application.

04:56.000 --> 05:02.000
I'm going to be focusing on a very useful type of projection, stereographic projection.

05:02.000 --> 05:16.000
I'm not going to go into too much detail on this, because Henry Segerman already has a great video

