05:36.000 --> 05:44.000
Okay, now that we have a better way to visualize spherical and hyperbolic space, we can start making some sense of its weird properties.

05:44.000 --> 05:53.000
But first, I have to talk about parallel lines. They don't exist in spherical space.

05:53.000 --> 06:02.000
Any pair of straight lines will always converge and intersect eventually, so the whole concept of two things being parallel is not a global property anymore.

06:02.000 --> 06:06.000
It's a local phenomena that only exists at a point on the line.

06:06.000 --> 06:10.000
And remember how everything hyperbolic is the opposite of spherical?

06:10.000 --> 06:14.000
Well, in hyperbolic space, lines will always diverge.

06:14.000 --> 06:18.000
Remember, both of these are straight lines, just like how this is actually a square.

06:18.000 --> 06:21.000
It just depends on what angle you're looking at it from.

06:21.000 --> 06:26.000
So walking over to the other line will shift the perspective to see it was straight the whole time.

06:26.000 --> 06:30.000
Speaking of walking, let's take a walk on the sphere.

06:30.000 --> 06:36.000
Let's walk up one tile, right one tile, and then down one tile.

06:36.000 --> 06:41.000
We're back where we started, and we just walked around a triangle with three right angles.

06:41.000 --> 06:49.000
In Euclidean space, a triangle's angles have to sum to 180 degrees, but in spherical space, it's always larger.

06:49.000 --> 06:53.000
But did you notice that something else weird happened?

06:53.000 --> 06:56.000
We walked around without ever changing our view direction.

06:56.000 --> 07:01.000
But when we came back to the starting point, everything's been rotated 90 degrees to the left.

07:01.000 --> 07:06.000
This is called halonomy, and it's something you don't experience in Euclidean geometry.

07:06.000 --> 07:14.000
Basically, as you move around the space, you accumulate extra rotation, even if you never change the direction you're facing.

07:14.000 --> 07:17.000
So take a guess what happens on a hyperbolic walk.

07:17.000 --> 07:30.000
We'll walk up one tile, right one tile, down one tile, left one tile, and finally up one more time.

07:30.000 --> 07:33.000
Now we've walked on a pentagon with five right angles.

07:33.000 --> 07:37.000
This time, the sum is less than you would expect for a Euclidean pentagon,

07:37.000 --> 07:42.000
because polygon angles have a smaller sum in hyperbolic space than Euclidean.

07:42.000 --> 07:48.000
And we have the same halonomy effect, but this time rotated in the opposite direction.

07:48.000 --> 07:51.000
One last effect I want to talk about is a physical one.

07:51.000 --> 07:58.000
In the real world, objects are made up of smaller particles, and when an object moves, all of its particles move as well.

07:58.000 --> 08:07.000
But remember, there's no parallel lines in curved space, so an object's particles can't actually all move in the same direction.

08:07.000 --> 08:14.000
In spherical geometry, this means you'd experience a sort of squishing tidal force as you try to move through space.

08:14.000 --> 08:20.000
This is very similar to spaghettification around a black hole, which is also caused by curved space.

08:20.000 --> 08:25.000
And in hyperbolic space, objects experience a stretching tidal force as they move.

08:25.000 --> 08:31.000
With enough speed and curvature, hitting a hyperbolic baseball could actually rip it apart.

08:31.000 --> 08:37.000
Okay, let's switch over to some formulas. How would a curved space affect the circumference of a circle?

08:37.000 --> 08:43.000
It's 2 pi r in Euclidean space, but it's pi sine r in spherical space.

08:43.000 --> 08:49.000
It should kind of make sense why this is true. As the radius gets larger, it reaches a maximum circumference,

08:49.000 --> 08:54.000
then shrinks down to zero, and repeats cyclically.

08:54.000 --> 08:57.000
Want to guess what the hyperbolic opposite is?

08:57.000 --> 09:03.000
It's hyperbolic sine, of course, and this is another really good example of just how large hyperbolic space is,

09:03.000 --> 09:06.000
because this is basically an exponential here.

09:06.000 --> 09:12.000
That means it could take a million times longer to walk around a circle than it would to just walk across it.

09:12.000 --> 09:16.000
The area of a circle also has similar formulas.

09:16.000 --> 09:23.000
Again, area is exponential for hyperbolic space, but interestingly, it grows at the same rate as the circumference,

09:23.000 --> 09:26.000
unlike Euclidean space where it grows as the square.

09:26.000 --> 09:32.000
The Pythagorean formula also has really beautiful analogs in curved space.

09:32.000 --> 09:37.000
And finally, this was one of the coolest formulas, and there's no Euclidean version of it.

09:37.000 --> 09:42.000
In a unit curved space, you can find the area of any triangle given only its angles.

09:42.000 --> 09:49.000
And the formula is so simple. For spherical space, it's just the sum of the angles minus pi. That's it.

09:49.000 --> 09:55.000
In hyperbolic space, it's pi minus the sum of the angles. Isn't that neat?

09:55.000 --> 10:01.000
And there's a good insight from this formula. Since the sum is always less than 180 degrees in hyperbolic space,

10:01.000 --> 10:10.000
it means there's actually a maximum possible area a triangle can have, and that's when all the angles are 0 degrees, and the area is pi.

10:10.000 --> 10:18.000
It happens because all lines eventually diverge, so if you tried to make the triangle any larger, the edges would never be able to intersect at a vertex.

